vectorData.altText: That’s right!  The deep inguinal ring (A) locates superior to the midpoint of the inguinal ligament. It can be located by identifying the inferior epigastric vessels.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
Remember, the deep inguinal ring is the point at which, during development, the testes pass from the extraperitoneal fascia through the transversalis fascia.

The deep inguinal ring is located immediately lateral to the inferior epigastric vessels.
The inferior epigastric vessels are a surgical landmark for the deep inguinal ring.

It is located just superior to the midpoint of the inguinal ligament, halfway between the ASIS and the pubic tubercle. In passing through the transversalis fascia, the testes and spermatic cord take a covering, the internal spermatic fascia.
